{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem \"Maa ka Khwab\" (\"Mother's Dream\"), from *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, the mother dreams of wandering in darkness and encountering a silent procession of boys dressed in emerald-green robes, each carrying a burning lamp. Her young son is among them but lags at the back, his own lamp extinguished. Distraught, she laments his absence and tearful days without him; he responds that her constant weeping has put out his lamp, hindering his progress.[^1][^2]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, \"Maa ka Khwab\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-1d110a).\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, \"Maa ka Khwab\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-4feffc).\n\nThe full poem is a short verse of 15 paragraphs describing this visionary encounter; the dream symbolizes how parental attachment and sorrow can impede a child's spiritual journey.[^3]\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 29 \"Maa ka Khwab\" [/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/].",
